                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>As you can see in the sentence above, verbs are not the only words to prefix the negative particle. The
                adverb
                '<em>æfre - ever/always</em>' becomes '<em>næfre</em>',
                while the pronoun in '<em>an mann</em>' meaning '<em>any man</em>' is
                prefixed
                with the negative particle '<em>ne</em>', to give us the negated pronoun '<em>nan - not any man</em>'.
                </p>
                <p>Other common negations you may commonly
                come across are '<em>nahwær - nowhere</em>',
                and
                '<em>nealles - not/not at all</em>'. Finally, the determiner 'no' in Old English
                is '<em>na</em>', so a question might be answered with '<em>gea - yes</em>' or '<em>na - no</em>'.
            </p>
            <p>Although in modern English double negations are not generally used, some dialects of English retain double negation. For
                example 'I don't know nothing' is a double negative that means 'I don't know anything'.
            </p>

